ve changed from 1948 to our present post-Cold War era. With a brisk, engaging style, Jacoby positions the case in the politics of the post-World War II era and then explores the ways in which generations of liberals and conservatives have put Chambers and Hiss to their own ideological uses. An iconic event of the McCarthy era, the case of Alger Hiss fascinates political intellectuals not only because of its historical significance but because of its timeless relevance to equally fierce debates today about the difficult balance between national security and respect for civil liberties.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCold War. 0aCommunismxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aCommunismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEspionage, SovietxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aEspionage, SovietzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical culturexUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aRight and left (Political science) 0aRight and left (Political science). 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300155846423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300155846.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles